    {
      "id": "OVcMOfOD1AYYwWzfmsPm3",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1685.5645495465612,
      "y": 11529.512297069074,
      "width": 1781.999267578125,
      "height": 3195,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#d0bfff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bEG",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 143390563,
      "version": 111,
      "versionNonce": 1704576099,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1770043200792,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Payment ->\n\nShort answer (clear & honest)\n\nWe need status in Payment only when payment is NOT an instant, one-shot operation.\nIf payment can fail, retry, stay pending, or be refunded, then Payment MUST have a status.\n\n\nThink of Payment as a STATE MACHINE 💳\n\nPayment is not money — it is a process.\n\nWhenever a process:\n\nspans time\ntalks to an external system\ncan be retried\ncan end in different outcomes\n👉 it needs a status.\n\nWhen Payment DOES NOT need status ❌\nSimple synchronous flow\npay() → success / failure → done\n\nExample:\n\nCash payment\nSimple in-memory demo\nOne API call, one response\n\nsuccess = gateway.pay(amount)\nif success:\n    invoice.status = \"PAID\"\n\nHere:\n\nPayment object is just a record\nInvoice status is enough\n\n\nWhen Payment MUST have status ✅ (Real systems)\n\nCase 1️⃣ Asynchronous gateways\n\nUPI / Card / Wallet\nINITIATED → PENDING → SUCCESS / FAILED\n\n\nWhy?\n\nGateway response may take time\nUser may close app\nCallback/webhook arrives later\n\nCase 2️⃣ Retry support\n\nFAILED → RETRY → SUCCESS\nYou need to know:\n\nHow many attempts?\nWhich one succeeded?\nWhich failed?\n\n\nCase 3️⃣ Partial payments\n\nPARTIAL → PENDING → COMPLETE\nExample:\n\nWallet + Card\nCoupon + Online payment",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Payment ->\n\nShort answer (clear & honest)\n\nWe need status in Payment only when payment is NOT an instant, one-shot operation.\nIf payment can fail, retry, stay pending, or be refunded, then Payment MUST have a status.\n\n\nThink of Payment as a STATE MACHINE 💳\n\nPayment is not money — it is a process.\n\nWhenever a process:\n\nspans time\ntalks to an external system\ncan be retried\ncan end in different outcomes\n👉 it needs a status.\n\nWhen Payment DOES NOT need status ❌\nSimple synchronous flow\npay() → success / failure → done\n\nExample:\n\nCash payment\nSimple in-memory demo\nOne API call, one response\n\nsuccess = gateway.pay(amount)\nif success:\n    invoice.status = \"PAID\"\n\nHere:\n\nPayment object is just a record\nInvoice status is enough\n\n\nWhen Payment MUST have status ✅ (Real systems)\n\nCase 1️⃣ Asynchronous gateways\n\nUPI / Card / Wallet\nINITIATED → PENDING → SUCCESS / FAILED\n\n\nWhy?\n\nGateway response may take time\nUser may close app\nCallback/webhook arrives later\n\nCase 2️⃣ Retry support\n\nFAILED → RETRY → SUCCESS\nYou need to know:\n\nHow many attempts?\nWhich one succeeded?\nWhich failed?\n\n\nCase 3️⃣ Partial payments\n\nPARTIAL → PENDING → COMPLETE\nExample:\n\nWallet + Card\nCoupon + Online payment",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
